# Project Blue nanoGPT: Local Real Estate Intelligence for Pima County, AZ 
Team 2 is proposing to build a small, focused AI model, or nanoGPT, trained specifically on public information relevant to the area affected by Project Blue in Pima County, Arizona. The goal is to create a local knowledge assistant that has been trained on information about neighborhoods, zoning, development plans, infrastructure projects, schools, transportation, and property trends near the Project Blue area that helps first-time home buyers quickly understand how the Project Blue area is growing and what it may mean for purchasing a home there. The assistant will answer questions and explain how development in the area may affect housing, infrastructure, and future neighborhood changes. 
The objective is to build an AI assistant that helps people understand how the Project Blue region is developing. A user could ask questions about housing development, crime rates, or other changes expected in the area. The system would summarize the relevant public documents and explain what those plans may mean for someone considering buying a home there. 
Today, buyers usually rely on real estate websites, real estate agents, or local news to learn about neighborhoods. While these sources provide useful information, important details about future development are often buried inside long planning documents or spread across multiple government websites. As a result, many first-time buyers make decisions without fully understanding how the area may change over time. 
The new approach in this project is to train a small AI model focused only on the Project Blue region and designed specifically for first-time home buyers. Instead of trying to understand information from everywhere, the system concentrates on one location and a clear set of documents. Because the scope is narrow and local, the assistant can provide clearer and more relevant explanations about development plans and community growth. 
Public information may be incomplete or may change as new development plans are announced. The system must also be updated regularly to remain accurate. To address this, the assistant will reference the original documents it uses so users can verify the information themselves. 
Success for the project will be measured in two stages. About half way through, the system should be able to read planning documents and summarize major housing or infrastructure projects in the Project Blue area. In the final stage, it should be able to answer questions from first-time home buyers about future development near a potential home purchase and explain those answers clearly using the underlying public records. 
 
